\f0\fs26 \cf2 Explain how a combination of various geological evidence from continental rock records or features contributed to the acceptance of the idea of continental drift.\
The idea of continental drift was first proposed by Alfred Wegener in the 1900s. He noticed that the continents seemed to fit together at the edge to their continental shelves, as well as the tracking of glacial deposits in the southern hemisphere. The occurrences of tillites an other glacial deposits, some as old as 300 million years, as well as matching rock structures on the complimentary coastal regions of South America and Africa and coal beds found across several continents suggest that the continents once comprised a larger super continent, known as Pangea. Evidence from the fossil record, including both triassic plant (Glossopteris) and animal (Cynogathus, Lystrosaurus) species also supports the theory of continental drift. These deposits, representing ancient glaciers and rock formations, and fossils representing creatures of the triassic period, could not have traversed the oceans, and thus provided the neccessary support the notion of an original singular continent that broke and spread apart over time. \
